---
import Docs from '../../layouts/Docs.astro';
import CopyCommand from '../../components/CopyCommand.astro';
import Code from '../../components/Code.astro';
import { href } from '../../lib/site';
---

<Docs
  title="Installation"
  eyebrow="Documentation · Start"
  summary="From a clean Ubuntu install to a working prompt. About three minutes, most of it apt."
>
  <h2 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Ubuntu 26.04 LTS (a fresh install is ideal, but not required).</li>
    <li>An internet connection and your <code>sudo</code> password.</li>
    <li><code>git</code> and <code>curl</code> — present on a default Ubuntu desktop; the bootstrap installs them if not.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="install">Install</h2>
  <p>Clone the repository and run the bootstrap:</p>
  <div class="not-prose my-6">
    <CopyCommand command="git clone https://github.com/etmartinkazoo/ubuntu_setup.git && cd ubuntu_setup && ./setup/bootstrap.sh" />
  </div>
  <p>
    The script asks for your password once (for <code>apt</code>), then runs
    unattended. When it finishes, restart your shell or open a new terminal:
  </p>
  <div class="not-prose my-6">
    <CopyCommand command="exec bash" />
  </div>

  <h2 id="what-happens">What happens, in order</h2>
  <p>The bootstrap runs a fixed sequence of small, self-contained steps:</p>
  <Code caption="setup/bootstrap.sh — stages">
    <span class="tok-prompt">→</span> preflight   check OS, sudo, network
    <span class="tok-prompt">→</span> apt         install the curated package set
    <span class="tok-prompt">→</span> herdr       install the terminal multiplexer
    <span class="tok-prompt">→</span> mise        runtimes: node, ruby, python
    <span class="tok-prompt">→</span> dotfiles    symlink bash, herdr, git into <span class="tok-comment">$HOME</span>
    <span class="tok-prompt">→</span> privacy     disable telemetry and phone-home
    <span class="tok-prompt">→</span> hardening   firewall, auto-updates, sysctl
    <span class="tok-prompt">→</span> power       battery tuning + framework fixes
  </Code>
  <p>
    Each stage is a separate file under <code>setup/steps/</code>. You can read
    any of them before running, or run one on its own — see
    <a href={href('/docs/customizing/')}>Customizing</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="idempotent">Safe to re-run</h2>
  <p>
    The bootstrap is idempotent. Run it again after pulling updates and it only
    applies what's changed. Before replacing any existing dotfile, it moves your
    current copy to a timestamped backup:
  </p>
  <Code>
    <span class="tok-comment"># your original files are never deleted</span>
    ~/.dotfiles-backup/2026-07-02T14-22-08/.bashrc
    ~/.dotfiles-backup/2026-07-02T14-22-08/config.toml
  </Code>

  <h2 id="unattended">Unattended installs</h2>
  <p>
    For provisioning a machine without prompts, set <code>ASSUME_YES=1</code>.
    This accepts defaults and skips interactive confirmations:
  </p>
  <div class="not-prose my-6">
    <CopyCommand command="ASSUME_YES=1 ./setup/bootstrap.sh" />
  </div>

  <h2 id="verify">Verify</h2>
  <p>
    Re-run the verification stage at any time to confirm your environment
    matches the repo:
  </p>
  <div class="not-prose my-6">
    <CopyCommand command="./setup/bootstrap.sh --verify" />
  </div>
  <p>
    From here, see <a href={href('/docs/whats-inside/')}>What's inside</a> for
    the full inventory, or <a href={href('/docs/customizing/')}>Customizing</a>
    to make it yours.
  </p>
</Docs>
